goTerms.name: membrane part
goTerms.definition: Any constituent part of a membrane, a double layer of lipid molecules that encloses all cells, and, in eukaryotes, many organelles; may be a single or double lipid bilayer; also includes associated proteins.
goTerms.comment: Note that this term is in the subset of terms that should not be used for direct gene product annotation. Instead, select a child term or, if no appropriate child term exists, please request a new term. Direct annotations to this term may be amended during annotation QC.

goTerms.name: oxidoreductase activity
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of an oxidation-reduction (redox) reaction, a reversible chemical reaction in which the oxidation state of an atom or atoms within a molecule is altered. One substrate acts as a hydrogen or electron donor and becomes oxidized, while the other acts as hydrogen or electron acceptor and becomes reduced.
goTerms.comment: Note that enzymes of class EC:1.97.-.- should also be annotated to this term.

goTerms.name: macromolecule biosynthetic process
goTerms.definition: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a macromolecule, any molecule of high relative molecular mass, the structure of which essentially comprises the multiple repetition of units derived, actually or conceptually, from molecules of low relative molecular mass.

goTerms.name: response to host defenses
goTerms.definition: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of detecting the defenses of the host organism. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

goTerms.name: heterocycle biosynthetic process
goTerms.definition: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of heterocyclic compounds, those with a cyclic molecular structure and at least two different atoms in the ring (or rings).

goTerms.name: oxidoreductase activity, acting on the CH-CH group of donors
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of an oxidation-reduction (redox) reaction in which a CH-CH group acts as a hydrogen or electron donor and reduces a hydrogen or electron acceptor.
goTerms.comment: Note that enzymes of class EC:1.3.99.- should also be annotated to this term.

goTerms.name: regulation of nucleobase-containing compound metabolic process
goTerms.definition: Any cellular process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving nucleobases, nucleosides, nucleotides and nucleic acids.

goTerms.name: purine ribonucleotide binding
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a purine ribonucleotide, any compound consisting of a purine ribonucleoside that is esterified with (ortho)phosphate or an oligophosphate at any hydroxyl group on the ribose moiety.

goTerms.name: catabolic process
goTerms.definition: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of substances, including the breakdown of carbon compounds with the liberation of energy for use by the cell or organism.

goTerms.name: regulation of biosynthetic process
goTerms.definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of substances.

goTerms.name: negative regulation by symbiont of host innate immune response
hydrolase activity
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of the hydrolysis of various bonds, e.g. C-O, C-N, C-C, phosphoric anhydride bonds, etc. Hydrolase is the systematic name for any enzyme of EC class 3.

goTerms.name: cellular macromolecule metabolic process
goTerms.definition: The chemical reactions and pathways involving macromolecules, any molecule of high relative molecular mass, the structure of which essentially comprises the multiple repetition of units derived, actually or conceptually, from molecules of low relative molecular mass, as carried out by individual cells.

goTerms.name: intracellular part
goTerms.definition: Any constituent part of the living contents of a cell; the matter contained within (but not including) the plasma membrane, usually taken to exclude large vacuoles and masses of secretory or ingested material. In eukaryotes it includes the nucleus and cytoplasm.
goTerms.comment: Note that this term is in the subset of terms that should not be used for direct gene product annotation. Instead, select a child term or, if no appropriate child term exists, please request a new term. Direct annotations to this term may be amended during annotation QC.

goTerms.name: intrinsic component of membrane
goTerms.definition: The component of a membrane consisting of the gene products having some covalently attached portion, for example part of a peptide sequence or some other covalently attached group such as a GPI anchor, which spans or is embedded in one or both leaflets of the membrane.
goTerms.comment: Note that proteins intrinsic to membranes cannot be removed without disrupting the membrane, e.g. by detergent.

goTerms.name: regulation of macromolecule metabolic process
goTerms.definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving macromolecules, any molecule of high relative molecular mass, the structure of which essentially comprises the multiple repetition of units derived, actually or conceptually, from molecules of low relative molecular mass.

goTerms.name: purine ribonucleoside binding
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a purine ribonucleoside, a compound consisting of a purine base linked to ribose.

goTerms.name: regulation of cellular biosynthetic process
goTerms.definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of substances, carried out by individual cells.

goTerms.name: response to other organism
goTerms.definition: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus from another living organism.

goTerms.name: anion binding
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with anions, charged atoms or groups of atoms with a net negative charge.

goTerms.name: regulation of macromolecule biosynthetic process
goTerms.definition: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a macromolecule, any molecule of high relative molecular mass, the structure of which essentially comprises the multiple repetition of units derived, actually or conceptually, from molecules of low relative molecular mass.

goTerms.name: sulfur compound transmembrane transporter activity
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of the transfer of a sulfur compound from one side of the membrane to the other.

goTerms.name: nitrogen compound metabolic process
goTerms.definition: The chemical reactions and pathways involving organic or inorganic compounds that contain nitrogen, including (but not limited to) nitrogen fixation, nitrification, denitrification, assimilatory/dissimilatory nitrate reduction and the interconversion of nitrogenous organic matter and ammonium.
goTerms.comment: Note that amino acid and derivative metabolism should not be annotated here. Instead use the 'amino acid and derivative metabolism' node.

goTerms.name: negative regulation of defense response
goTerms.definition: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of a defense response.

goTerms.name: multi-organism process
goTerms.definition: A biological process which involves another organism of the same or different species.

goTerms.name: transition metal ion binding
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a transition metal ions; a transition metal is an element whose atom has an incomplete d-subshell of extranuclear electrons, or which gives rise to a cation or cations with an incomplete d-subshell. Transition metals often have more than one valency state. Biologically relevant transition metals include vanadium, manganese, iron, copper, cobalt, nickel, molybdenum and silver.

goTerms.name: negative regulation of immune system process
goTerms.definition: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate, or extent of an immune system process.

goTerms.name: nucleobase-containing compound metabolic process
goTerms.definition: Any cellular metabolic process involving nucleobases, nucleosides, nucleotides and nucleic acids.

goTerms.name: ATPase activity, coupled
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O = ADP + phosphate; this reaction directly drives some other reaction, for example ion transport across a membrane.

goTerms.name: response to external stimulus
goTerms.definition: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an external stimulus.
goTerms.comment: Note that this term is in the subset of terms that should not be used for direct gene product annotation. Instead, select a child term or, if no appropriate child term exists, please request a new term. Direct annotations to this term may be amended during annotation QC.

goTerms.name: regulation of gene expression
goTerms.definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of gene expression. Gene expression is the process in which a gene's coding sequence is converted into a mature gene product or products (proteins or RNA). This includes the production of an RNA transcript as well as any processing to produce a mature RNA product or an mRNA (for protein-coding genes) and the translation of that mRNA into protein. Some protein processing events may be included when they are required to form an active form of a product from an inactive precursor form.

goTerms.name: modulation by organism of immune response of other organism involved in symbiotic interaction
goTerms.definition: Any process in which an organism modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the immune response of a second organism, where the two organisms are in a symbiotic interaction. The immune response is any immune system process that functions in the calibrated response of an organism to a potential internal or invasive threat.

goTerms.name: cellular nitrogen compound metabolic process
goTerms.definition: The chemical reactions and pathways involving various organic and inorganic nitrogenous compounds, as carried out by individual cells.

goTerms.name: single-organism transport
goTerms.definition: The directed movement of substances (such as macromolecules, small molecules, ions) into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, or within a multicellular organism by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore, involving a single organism.

goTerms.name: modulation by symbiont of host immune response
goTerms.definition: Any process in which an organism modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the immune response of the host organism; the immune response is any immune system process that functions in the calibrated response of an organism to a potential internal or invasive threat. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

goTerms.name: nucleoside-triphosphatase activity
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: a nucleoside triphosphate + H2O = nucleoside diphosphate + phosphate.

goTerms.name: primary metabolic process
goTerms.definition: The chemical reactions and pathways involving those compounds which are formed as a part of the normal anabolic and catabolic processes. These processes take place in most, if not all, cells of the organism.

goTerms.name: regulation of cellular macromolecule biosynthetic process
goTerms.definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cellular macromolecule biosynthetic process.

goTerms.name: nucleic acid binding transcription factor activity
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a DNA or RNA sequence in order to modulate transcription. The transcription factor may or may not also interact selectively with a protein or macromolecular complex.
goTerms.comment: Note that this term is in the subset of terms that should not be used for direct gene product annotation. This term does not provide specificity with respect to the type of nucleic acid binding, e.g. RNA or DNA. Please use a child term that provides that specificity or, if no appropriate child term exists, please request a new term. Direct annotations to this term may be amended during annotation QC.

goTerms.name: nucleoside phosphate binding
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with nucleoside phosphate.

goTerms.name: sulfate transmembrane transporter activity
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of the transfer of sulfate ions, SO4(2-), from one side of a membrane to the other.

goTerms.name: biological_process
goTerms.definition: Any process specifically pertinent to the functioning of integrated living units: cells, tissues, organs, and organisms. A process is a collection of molecular events with a defined beginning and end.
goTerms.comment: Note that, in addition to forming the root of the biological process ontology, this term is recommended for use for the annotation of gene products whose biological process is unknown. Note that when this term is used for annotation, it indicates that no information was available about the biological process of the gene product annotated as of the date the annotation was made; the evidence code ND, no data, is used to indicate this.

goTerms.name: adenyl nucleotide binding
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with adenyl nucleotides, any compound consisting of adenosine esterified with (ortho)phosphate.

goTerms.name: nucleobase-containing compound biosynthetic process
goTerms.definition: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of nucleobases, nucleosides, nucleotides and nucleic acids.

goTerms.name: substrate-specific transporter activity
goTerms.definition: Enables the directed movement of a specific substance or group of related substances (such as macromolecules, small molecules, ions) into, out of or within a cell, or between cells.

goTerms.name: ATPase activity, coupled to transmembrane movement of substances
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O = ADP + phosphate, to directly drive the active transport of a substance across a membrane.

goTerms.name: oxidoreductase activity, acting on peroxide as acceptor
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of an oxidation-reduction (redox) reaction in which the peroxide group acts as a hydrogen or electron acceptor.

goTerms.name: response to external biotic stimulus
goTerms.definition: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an external biotic stimulus, an external stimulus caused by, or produced by living things.

goTerms.name: organic substance metabolic process
goTerms.definition: The chemical reactions and pathways involving an organic substance, any molecular entity containing carbon.

goTerms.name: external encapsulating structure
goTerms.definition: A structure that lies outside the plasma membrane and surrounds the entire cell.

goTerms.name: RNA biosynthetic process
goTerms.definition: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of RNA, ribonucleic acid, one of the two main type of nucleic acid, consisting of a long, unbranched macromolecule formed from ribonucleotides joined in 3',5'-phosphodiester linkage. Includes polymerization of ribonucleotide monomers. Refers not only to transcription but also to e.g. viral RNA replication.
goTerms.comment: Note that, in some cases, viral RNA replication and viral transcription from RNA actually refer to the same process, but may be called differently depending on the focus of a specific research study.

goTerms.name: substrate-specific transmembrane transporter activity
goTerms.definition: Enables the transfer of a specific substance or group of related substances from one side of a membrane to the other.

goTerms.name: nucleic acid metabolic process
goTerms.definition: Any cellular metabolic process involving nucleic acids.

goTerms.name: regulation of response to stress
goTerms.definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of a response to stress. Response to stress is a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a disturbance in organismal or cellular homeostasis, usually, but not necessarily, exogenous (e.g. temperature, humidity, ionizing radiation).
goTerms.comment: Note that this term is in the subset of terms that should not be used for direct gene product annotation. Instead, select a child term or, if no appropriate child term exists, please request a new term. Direct annotations to this term may be amended during annotation QC.

goTerms.name: phosphoric ester hydrolase activity
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: RPO-R' + H2O = RPOOH + R'H. This reaction is the hydrolysis of any phosphoric ester bond, any ester formed from orthophosphoric acid, O=P(OH)3.

goTerms.name: modulation by organism of defense response of other organism involved in symbiotic interaction
goTerms.definition: Any process in which an organism modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the defense response of a second organism, the response mounted by that organism in response to the presence of the first organism, where the two organisms are in a symbiotic interaction.

goTerms.name: modulation by symbiont of host defense response
goTerms.definition: Any process in which an organism modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the defense response of its host, the response mounted by the host in response to the presence of the organism. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

goTerms.name: inorganic anion transmembrane transporter activity
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of the transfer of inorganic anions from one side of a membrane to the other. Inorganic anions are atoms or small molecules with a negative charge which do not contain carbon in covalent linkage.

goTerms.name: binding
goTerms.definition: The selective, non-covalent, often stoichiometric, interaction of a molecule with one or more specific sites on another molecule.
goTerms.comment: Note that this term is in the subset of terms that should not be used for direct, manual gene product annotation. Please choose a more specific child term, or request a new one if no suitable term is available. For ligands that bind to signal transducing receptors, consider the molecular function term 'receptor binding ; GO:0005102' and its children.

goTerms.name: suppression of defense response of other organism involved in symbiotic interaction
goTerms.definition: Any process in which an organism stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the defense response of a second organism, where the two organisms are in a symbiotic interaction.

goTerms.name: ribonucleotide binding
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a ribonucleotide, any compound consisting of a ribonucleoside that is esterified with (ortho)phosphate or an oligophosphate at any hydroxyl group on the ribose moiety.

goTerms.name: establishment of localization
goTerms.definition: The directed movement of a cell, substance or cellular entity, such as a protein complex or organelle, to a specific location.

goTerms.name: macromolecule metabolic process
goTerms.definition: The chemical reactions and pathways involving macromolecules, any molecule of high relative molecular mass, the structure of which essentially comprises the multiple repetition of units derived, actually or conceptually, from molecules of low relative molecular mass.

goTerms.name: single-organism cellular process
goTerms.definition: Any process that is carried out at the cellular level, occurring within a single organism.

goTerms.name: hydrolase activity, acting on ester bonds
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of the hydrolysis of any ester bond.

goTerms.name: negative regulation by organism of innate immune response in other organism involved in symbiotic interaction
goTerms.definition: Any process in which an organism stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the innate immune response of a second organism, where the two organisms are in a symbiotic interaction.

goTerms.name: active transmembrane transporter activity
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of the transfer of a specific substance or related group of substances from one side of a membrane to the other, up the solute's concentration gradient. The transporter binds the solute and undergoes a series of conformational changes. Transport works equally well in either direction.

goTerms.name: pyrophosphatase activity
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of the hydrolysis of a pyrophosphate bond between two phosphate groups, leaving one phosphate on each of the two fragments.

goTerms.name: regulation of response to stimulus
goTerms.definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of a response to a stimulus. Response to stimulus is a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus.
goTerms.comment: Note that this term is in the subset of terms that should not be used for direct gene product annotation. Instead, select a child term or, if no appropriate child term exists, please request a new term. Direct annotations to this term may be amended during annotation QC.

goTerms.name: response to host
goTerms.definition: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of the symbiont or its cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of detecting molecules of its host organism. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.
goTerms.comment: Note that this term is used to annotate gene products of the symbiont.

goTerms.name: intrinsic component of plasma membrane
goTerms.definition: The component of the plasma membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that have some covalently attached part (e.g. peptide sequence or GPI anchor), which spans or is embedded in one or both leaflets of the membrane.

goTerms.name: transferase activity, transferring nitrogenous groups
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of the transfer of a nitrogenous group from one compound (donor) to another (acceptor).
goTerms.comment: Note that enzymes of class EC:2.6.99.- should also be annotated to this term.

goTerms.name: cofactor binding
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a cofactor, a substance that is required for the activity of an enzyme or other protein. Cofactors may be inorganic, such as the metal atoms zinc, iron, and copper in certain forms, or organic, in which case they are referred to as coenzymes. Cofactors may either be bound tightly to active sites or bind loosely with the substrate.

goTerms.name: transmembrane transporter activity
goTerms.definition: Enables the transfer of a substance from one side of a membrane to the other.

goTerms.name: organic cyclic compound binding
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with an organic cyclic compound, any molecular entity that contains carbon arranged in a cyclic molecular structure.

goTerms.name: negative regulation of biological process
goTerms.definition: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of a biological process. Biological processes are regulated by many means; examples include the control of gene expression, protein modification or interaction with a protein or substrate molecule.

goTerms.name: biological regulation
goTerms.definition: Any process that modulates a measurable attribute of any biological process, quality or function.

goTerms.name: antioxidant activity
goTerms.definition: Inhibition of the reactions brought about by dioxygen (O2) or peroxides. Usually the antioxidant is effective because it can itself be more easily oxidized than the substance protected. The term is often applied to components that can trap free radicals, thereby breaking the chain reaction that normally leads to extensive biological damage.

goTerms.name: avoidance of defenses of other organism involved in symbiotic interaction
goTerms.definition: Any process, either constitutive or induced, by which an organism evades, minimizes, or suppresses the effects of a second organism's defense(s), where the two organisms are in a symbiotic interaction.

goTerms.name: cell part
goTerms.definition: Any constituent part of a cell, the basic structural and functional unit of all organisms.
goTerms.comment: Note that this term is in the subset of terms that should not be used for direct gene product annotation. Instead, select a child term or, if no appropriate child term exists, please request a new term. Direct annotations to this term may be amended during annotation QC.

goTerms.name: cellular catabolic process
goTerms.definition: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of substances, carried out by individual cells.

goTerms.name: interaction with host
goTerms.definition: An interaction between two organisms living together in more or less intimate association. The term host is used for the larger (macro) of the two members of a symbiosis; the various forms of symbiosis include parasitism, commensalism and mutualism.

goTerms.name: negative regulation by symbiont of host immune response
goTerms.definition: Any process in which an organism stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the immune response of the host organism; the immune response is any immune system process that functions in the calibrated response of an organism to a potential internal or invasive threat. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

goTerms.name: single-organism localization
goTerms.definition: A localization which involves only one organism.

goTerms.name: regulation of biological quality
goTerms.definition: Any process that modulates a qualitative or quantitative trait of a biological quality. A biological quality is a measurable attribute of an organism or part of an organism, such as size, mass, shape, color, etc.

goTerms.name: ATPase activity, coupled to movement of substances
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O = ADP + phosphate, to directly drive the transport of a substance.

goTerms.name: primary active transmembrane transporter activity
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of the transfer of a solute from one side of the membrane to the other, up the solute's concentration gradient, by binding the solute and undergoing a series of conformational changes. Transport works equally well in either direction and is powered by a primary energy source, directly using ATP. Primary energy sources known to be coupled to transport are chemical, electrical and solar sources.

goTerms.name: response to host immune response
goTerms.definition: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of detecting the immune response of the host organism. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

goTerms.name: sulfuric ester hydrolase activity
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of the reaction: RSO-R' + H2O = RSOOH + R'H. This reaction is the hydrolysis of any sulfuric ester bond, any ester formed from sulfuric acid, O=SO(OH)2.

goTerms.name: cellular metabolic process
goTerms.definition: The chemical reactions and pathways by which individual cells transform chemical substances.

goTerms.name: organic cyclic compound metabolic process
goTerms.definition: The chemical reactions and pathways involving organic cyclic compound.

goTerms.name: negative regulation of response to stimulus
goTerms.definition: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of a response to a stimulus. Response to stimulus is a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus.
goTerms.comment: Note that this term is in the subset of terms that should not be used for direct gene product annotation. Instead, select a child term or, if no appropriate child term exists, please request a new term. Direct annotations to this term may be amended during annotation QC.

goTerms.name: response to stimulus
goTerms.definition: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus. The process begins with detection of the stimulus and ends with a change in state or activity or the cell or organism.
goTerms.comment: Note that this term is in the subset of terms that should not be used for direct gene product annotation. Instead, select a child term or, if no appropriate child term exists, please request a new term. Direct annotations to this term may be amended during annotation QC.

goTerms.name: regulation of nitrogen compound metabolic process
goTerms.definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving nitrogen or nitrogenous compounds.

goTerms.name: regulation of RNA biosynthetic process
goTerms.definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of RNA biosynthetic process.

goTerms.name: purine ribonucleoside triphosphate binding
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a purine ribonucleoside triphosphate, a compound consisting of a purine base linked to a ribose sugar esterified with triphosphate on the sugar.

goTerms.name: interspecies interaction between organisms
goTerms.definition: Any process in which an organism has an effect on an organism of a different species.

goTerms.name: modification by symbiont of host morphology or physiology
goTerms.definition: The process in which a symbiont organism effects a change in the structure or processes of its host organism.

goTerms.name: sequence-specific DNA binding transcription factor activity
heterocyclic compound binding
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with heterocyclic compound.

goTerms.name: cellular_component
goTerms.definition: The part of a cell or its extracellular environment in which a gene product is located. A gene product may be located in one or more parts of a cell and its location may be as specific as a particular macromolecular complex, that is, a stable, persistent association of macromolecules that function together.
goTerms.comment: Note that, in addition to forming the root of the cellular component ontology, this term is recommended for use for the annotation of gene products whose cellular component is unknown. Note that when this term is used for annotation, it indicates that no information was available about the cellular component of the gene product annotated as of the date the annotation was made; the evidence code ND, no data, is used to indicate this.

goTerms.name: localization
goTerms.definition: Any process in which a cell, a substance, or a cellular entity, such as a protein complex or organelle, is transported to or maintained in a specific location.

goTerms.name: suppression of defenses of other organism involved in symbiotic interaction
goTerms.definition: Any process in which an organism stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the defense(s) of a second organism, where the two organisms are in a symbiotic interaction. Suppression occurs by active mechanisms that normally result in the shutting down of pathways in the second organism.

goTerms.name: ribonucleoside binding
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a ribonucleoside, a compound consisting of a purine or pyrimidine nitrogenous base linked to ribose.

goTerms.name: P-P-bond-hydrolysis-driven transmembrane transporter activity
goTerms.definition: Primary active transport of a solute across a membrane, driven by the hydrolysis of the diphosphate bond of inorganic pyrophosphate, ATP, or another nucleoside triphosphate. The transport protein may or may not be transiently phosphorylated, but the substrate is not phosphorylated. Primary active transport is catalysis of the transport of a solute across a membrane, up the solute's concentration gradient, by binding the solute and undergoing a series of conformational changes. Transport works equally well in either direction and is driven by a primary energy source.

goTerms.name: oxidoreductase complex
goTerms.definition: Any protein complex that possesses oxidoreductase activity.

goTerms.name: organic cyclic compound biosynthetic process
goTerms.definition: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of organic cyclic compound.

goTerms.name: nucleoside binding
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a nucleoside, a compound consisting of a purine or pyrimidine nitrogenous base linked either to ribose or deoxyribose.

goTerms.name: anion transmembrane-transporting ATPase activity
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction: ATP + H2O + anion(out) = ADP + phosphate + anion(in).

goTerms.name: avoidance of host defenses
goTerms.definition: Any process, either constitutive or induced, by which an organism evades, suppresses or tolerates the effects of its host organism's defense(s). Host defenses may be induced by the presence of the organism or may be preformed (e.g. physical barriers). The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

goTerms.name: regulation of biological process
goTerms.definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of a biological process. Biological processes are regulated by many means; examples include the control of gene expression, protein modification or interaction with a protein or substrate molecule.

goTerms.name: purine nucleoside binding
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a purine nucleoside, a compound consisting of a purine base linked either to ribose or deoxyribose.

goTerms.name: aromatic compound biosynthetic process
goTerms.definition: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of aromatic compounds, any substance containing an aromatic carbon ring.

goTerms.name: adenyl ribonucleotide binding
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with an adenyl ribonucleotide, any compound consisting of adenosine esterified with (ortho)phosphate or an oligophosphate at any hydroxyl group on the ribose moiety.

goTerms.name: regulation of immune system process
goTerms.definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate, or extent of an immune system process.

goTerms.name: suppression of host defenses
goTerms.definition: Any process in which an organism stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of host defense(s) by active mechanisms that normally result in the shutting down of a host pathway. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

goTerms.name: regulation of RNA metabolic process
goTerms.definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways involving RNA.

goTerms.name: response to immune response of other organism involved in symbiotic interaction
goTerms.definition: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of detecting the immune response of a second organism, where the two organisms are in a symbiotic interaction.

goTerms.name: transporter activity
goTerms.definition: Enables the directed movement of substances (such as macromolecules, small molecules, ions) into, out of or within a cell, or between cells.

goTerms.name: organic substance biosynthetic process
goTerms.definition: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of an organic substance, any molecular entity containing carbon.

goTerms.name: modulation by symbiont of host innate immune response
goTerms.definition: Any process in which an organism modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the innate immune response of the host organism; the innate immune response is the host's first line of defense against infection. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

goTerms.name: cellular macromolecule biosynthetic process
goTerms.definition: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a macromolecule, any molecule of high relative molecular mass, the structure of which essentially comprises the multiple repetition of units derived, actually or conceptually, from molecules of low relative molecular mass, carried out by individual cells.

goTerms.name: single-organism process
goTerms.definition: A biological process that involves only one organism.

goTerms.name: macromolecular complex
goTerms.definition: A stable assembly of two or more macromolecules, i.e. proteins, nucleic acids, carbohydrates or lipids, in which the constituent parts function together.

goTerms.name: negative regulation by symbiont of host defense response
goTerms.definition: Any process in which an organism stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the defense response of the host organism. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

goTerms.name: regulation of nucleic acid-templated transcription
goTerms.definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of nucleic acid-templated transcription.

goTerms.name: transferase activity, transferring acyl groups
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of the transfer of an acyl group from one compound (donor) to another (acceptor).

goTerms.name: negative regulation of innate immune response
goTerms.definition: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the innate immune response.

goTerms.name: nucleic acid binding
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with any nucleic acid.

goTerms.name: coenzyme binding
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a coenzyme, any of various nonprotein organic cofactors that are required, in addition to an enzyme and a substrate, for an enzymatic reaction to proceed.

goTerms.name: response to biotic stimulus
goTerms.definition: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a biotic stimulus, a stimulus caused or produced by a living organism.
goTerms.comment: Note that this term is in the subset of terms that should not be used for direct gene product annotation. Instead, select a child term or, if no appropriate child term exists, please request a new term. Direct annotations to this term may be amended during annotation QC.

goTerms.name: ion transmembrane transporter activity
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of the transfer of an ion from one side of a membrane to the other.

goTerms.name: cation binding
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with cations, charged atoms or groups of atoms with a net positive charge.

goTerms.name: regulation of cellular metabolic process
goTerms.definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways by which individual cells transform chemical substances.

goTerms.name: cellular process
goTerms.definition: Any process that is carried out at the cellular level, but not necessarily restricted to a single cell. For example, cell communication occurs among more than one cell, but occurs at the cellular level.

goTerms.name: regulation of innate immune response
goTerms.definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the innate immune response, the organism's first line of defense against infection.

goTerms.name: purine nucleotide binding
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with purine nucleotides, any compound consisting of a purine nucleoside esterified with (ortho)phosphate.

goTerms.name: cellular nitrogen compound biosynthetic process
goTerms.definition: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of organic and inorganic nitrogenous compounds.

goTerms.name: biosynthetic process
goTerms.definition: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of substances; typically the energy-requiring part of metabolism in which simpler substances are transformed into more complex ones.

goTerms.name: heterocycle metabolic process
goTerms.definition: The chemical reactions and pathways involving heterocyclic compounds, those with a cyclic molecular structure and at least two different atoms in the ring (or rings).

goTerms.name: regulation of metabolic process
goTerms.definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways within a cell or an organism.

goTerms.name: negative regulation by organism of immune response of other organism involved in symbiotic interaction
goTerms.definition: Any process in which an organism stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the immune response of a second organism, where the two organisms are in a symbiotic interaction. The immune response is any immune system process that functions in the calibrated response of an organism to a potential internal or invasive threat.

goTerms.name: metabolic process
goTerms.definition: The chemical reactions and pathways, including anabolism and catabolism, by which living organisms transform chemical substances. Metabolic processes typically transform small molecules, but also include macromolecular processes such as DNA repair and replication, and protein synthesis and degradation.
goTerms.comment: Note that metabolic processes do not include single functions or processes such as protein-protein interactions, protein-nucleic acids, nor receptor-ligand interactions.

goTerms.name: response to defenses of other organism involved in symbiotic interaction
goTerms.definition: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of detecting the defenses of a second organism, where the two organisms are in a symbiotic interaction.

goTerms.name: regulation of primary metabolic process
goTerms.definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways within a cell or an organism involving those compounds formed as a part of the normal anabolic and catabolic processes. These processes take place in most, if not all, cells of the organism.

goTerms.name: hydrolase activity, acting on acid anhydrides, in phosphorus-containing anhydrides
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of the hydrolysis of any acid anhydride which contains phosphorus.

goTerms.name: RNA metabolic process
goTerms.definition: The cellular chemical reactions and pathways involving RNA, ribonucleic acid, one of the two main type of nucleic acid, consisting of a long, unbranched macromolecule formed from ribonucleotides joined in 3',5'-phosphodiester linkage.

goTerms.name: carbohydrate derivative binding
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a carbohydrate derivative.

goTerms.name: cellular aromatic compound metabolic process
goTerms.definition: The chemical reactions and pathways involving aromatic compounds, any organic compound characterized by one or more planar rings, each of which contains conjugated double bonds and delocalized pi electrons, as carried out by individual cells.

goTerms.name: catalytic complex
goTerms.definition: A protein complex which is capable of catalytic activity.

goTerms.name: ion binding
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with ions, charged atoms or groups of atoms.

goTerms.name: anion transmembrane transporter activity
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of the transfer of a negatively charged ion from one side of a membrane to the other.

goTerms.name: iron ion binding
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with iron (Fe) ions.

goTerms.name: nucleotide binding
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a nucleotide, any compound consisting of a nucleoside that is esterified with (ortho)phosphate or an oligophosphate at any hydroxyl group on the ribose or deoxyribose.

goTerms.name: plasma membrane part
goTerms.definition: Any constituent part of the plasma membrane, the membrane surrounding a cell that separates the cell from its external environment. It consists of a phospholipid bilayer and associated proteins.
goTerms.comment: Note that this term is in the subset of terms that should not be used for direct gene product annotation. Instead, select a child term or, if no appropriate child term exists, please request a new term. Direct annotations to this term may be amended during annotation QC.

goTerms.name: molecular_function
goTerms.definition: Elemental activities, such as catalysis or binding, describing the actions of a gene product at the molecular level. A given gene product may exhibit one or more molecular functions.
goTerms.comment: Note that, in addition to forming the root of the molecular function ontology, this term is recommended for use for the annotation of gene products whose molecular function is unknown. Note that when this term is used for annotation, it indicates that no information was available about the molecular function of the gene product annotated as of the date the annotation was made; the evidence code ND, no data, is used to indicate this.

goTerms.name: hydrolase activity, acting on acid anhydrides, catalyzing transmembrane movement of substances
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of the hydrolysis of an acid anhydride to directly drive the transport of a substance across a membrane.

goTerms.name: regulation of defense response
goTerms.definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of a defense response.

goTerms.name: negative regulation of immune response
goTerms.definition: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the immune response, the immunological reaction of an organism to an immunogenic stimulus.

goTerms.name: modification of morphology or physiology of other organism involved in symbiotic interaction
goTerms.definition: The process in which an organism effects a change in the structure or processes of a second organism, where the two organisms are in a symbiotic interaction.

goTerms.name: modification of morphology or physiology of other organism
goTerms.definition: The process in which an organism effects a change in the structure or processes of a second organism.

goTerms.name: protein complex
goTerms.definition: Any macromolecular complex composed (only) of two or more polypeptide subunits along with any covalently attached molecules (such as lipid anchors or oligosaccharide) or non-protein prosthetic groups (such as nucleotides or metal ions). Prosthetic group in this context refers to a tightly bound cofactor. The component polypeptide subunits may be identical.

goTerms.name: transferase activity, transferring acyl groups other than amino-acyl groups
regulation of cellular process
goTerms.definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of a cellular process, any of those that are carried out at the cellular level, but are not necessarily restricted to a single cell. For example, cell communication occurs among more than one cell, but occurs at the cellular level.

goTerms.name: ATPase activity, coupled to transmembrane movement of ions
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of the transfer of an ion from one side of a membrane to the other, driven by the reaction: ATP + H2O = ADP + phosphate.

goTerms.name: DNA metabolic process
goTerms.definition: Any cellular metabolic process involving deoxyribonucleic acid. This is one of the two main types of nucleic acid, consisting of a long, unbranched macromolecule formed from one, or more commonly, two, strands of linked deoxyribonucleotides.

goTerms.name: hydrolase activity, acting on acid anhydrides
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of the hydrolysis of any acid anhydride.

goTerms.name: small molecule binding
goTerms.definition: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a small molecule, any low molecular weight, monomeric, non-encoded molecule.
goTerms.comment: Small molecules in GO include monosaccharides but exclude disaccharides and polysaccharides.

goTerms.name: cellular biosynthetic process
goTerms.definition: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of substances, carried out by individual cells.

goTerms.name: modulation by organism of innate immune response in other organism involved in symbiotic interaction
goTerms.definition: Any process in which an organism modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the innate immune response, the first line of defense against infection, of a second organism, where the two organisms are in a symbiotic interaction.

goTerms.name: oxidoreductase activity, acting on other nitrogenous compounds as donors
goTerms.definition: Catalysis of an oxidation-reduction (redox) reaction in which a nitrogenous group, excluding NH and NH2 groups, acts as a hydrogen or electron donor and reduces a hydrogen or electron acceptor.
goTerms.comment: Note that enzymes of class EC:1.7.99.- should also be annotated to this term.

goTerms.name: nucleic acid-templated transcription
goTerms.definition: The cellular synthesis of RNA on a template of nucleic acid (DNA or RNA).
goTerms.comment: Note that this term is in the subset of terms that should not be used for direct gene product annotation. Instead, select a child term or, if no appropriate child term exists, please request a new term. Direct annotations to this term may be amended during annotation QC.

goTerms.name: regulation of immune response
goTerms.definition: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the immune response, the immunological reaction of an organism to an immunogenic stimulus.
